This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane.

00:45.000 --> 00:49.280
Of all the themes handled by science fiction authors, that of alien contact has been one

00:49.280 --> 00:51.380
of the most consistently popular and fascinating.

00:51.380 --> 00:56.260
For a good reason too. Aliens, whether they be the hostile bug-eyed monsters of the old

00:56.260 --> 00:59.600
pulp magazines or the friendly creatures of close encounters of the third kind,

01:00.180 --> 01:02.520
have always been one of the biggest attractions of science fiction.

01:03.100 --> 01:06.620
In the past, stories of alien contact were usually written as thrillers,

01:06.960 --> 01:09.620
with the sole and simple intention of scaring readers.

01:10.260 --> 01:14.960
HD Wells, The War of the Worlds is probably the best example of that type of story.

01:15.220 --> 01:20.200
But that's changed. Many contemporary writers have provided more thoughtful treatments of aliens,

01:20.200 --> 01:24.120
deepening the realism and the significance of narratives of alien contact.

01:31.820 --> 01:36.720
Of course, before you can have a story of alien contact, you have to have some aliens.

01:37.320 --> 01:41.260
One of the most provocative descriptions of aliens in all of science fiction is found in

01:41.260 --> 01:44.600
Larry Nivens and Jerry Pornell's The Moat in God's Eye.

01:45.020 --> 01:48.620
The success of that book is largely due to the unique and ingenious aliens,

01:48.620 --> 01:51.340
the modis that Niven created for the story.

01:51.700 --> 01:55.780
It's interesting though that Niven says he doesn't really create aliens for a story,

01:56.180 --> 01:58.040
but suggests that it's the other way around.

01:58.960 --> 02:07.000
I always design aliens for themselves. I almost never design an alien to match a story.

02:07.640 --> 02:14.300
The story, some story will eventually include the alien. The alien stands for itself.

02:15.040 --> 02:19.240
There are two particularly fascinating things that Niven incorporated into these modis.

02:19.740 --> 02:25.080
One is the fact that they are not symmetrical. They have a head, torso, legs and arms as humans do,

02:25.480 --> 02:29.580
but the arms are disproportionate. One is small and thin, the other is large and powerful.

02:29.940 --> 02:34.560
Right. Niven says he took that idea from studying the structures of living creatures on Earth.

02:35.240 --> 02:43.100
In that case, I had the idea that I was following a progression with a protozoan,

02:43.100 --> 02:47.540
with an amoeba. You get radio symmetry inside and out.

02:48.900 --> 02:55.600
Move up a goodly distance and you find starfishes with radio symmetry on the outside and bilateral

02:55.600 --> 03:01.400
symmetry on the inside. Move up a little further, you find flat worms and worms of all

03:01.400 --> 03:09.680
stance. At the level of bilateral symmetry inside and out, go as far as a human, you find

03:09.680 --> 03:17.840
bilateral symmetry on the outside and no symmetry, well, half symmetrical on the inside.

03:18.260 --> 03:24.100
The lungs look symmetrical, the kidneys look symmetrical, the intestines look like somebody

03:24.100 --> 03:32.860
dropped a plate of spaghetti. I tried to move on to the next step, bilaterally unsymmetrical

03:32.860 --> 03:38.820
on the outside and I got the original Modi, the engineer for them.

03:49.920 --> 03:54.440
The other ingenious idea Niven developed for the Modi's is the way they construct and use machines.

03:55.220 --> 03:59.700
They're highly skilled tool users, but they have no standard pre-manufactured machines,

03:59.700 --> 04:04.540
parts or tools. They simply alter or reshape whatever they find around them at the time to

04:04.540 --> 04:10.060
suit their needs. Niven says that particular idea just came to him. It seemed interesting and even

04:10.060 --> 04:16.600
logical. I was just playing with the ideas at that point and that one seemed like a fun one.

04:17.160 --> 04:24.840
It also seemed likely enough if you've got a critter with not much intelligence except in

04:24.840 --> 04:34.460
the direction of tool making and tool altering, then why not? The thing has to keep testing its

04:34.460 --> 04:40.820
ability or it will lose it. It might as well be designing something every time it needs a specific

04:40.820 --> 04:47.360
machine. Besides the ingenuity Niven demonstrated in creating the Modi's, he and Pornell also weaved

04:47.360 --> 04:52.280
some unexpected twists into the first contact theme. Our reader interested in aliens are more

04:52.280 --> 04:56.140
specifically in first contact. Can't afford to overlook the Moten Ghat's eye.

