06:29.460 --> 06:33.680
This is Daryl Lane and to Bill Vernon. The so-called New Wave in Science Fiction,

06:33.800 --> 06:37.460
which began in the mid 60s, was simply a new way of writing traditional science fiction.

06:38.120 --> 06:42.400
There were changes for instance and characterization was given more emphasis.

06:44.580 --> 06:47.020
Sex and religion that science fiction had really

06:48.120 --> 06:55.060
New Wave changed the stereotype science fiction formula since the pulp days of the 20s, 30s and 40s.

06:55.660 --> 06:59.840
Frederick Poll, who's been an author and editor and an agent in the field of science fiction,

07:00.260 --> 07:01.700
has something to say about that change.

07:02.920 --> 07:10.200
New Wave was an attempt to I guess 15 years ago or more of a number of writers to break away from

07:10.200 --> 07:15.020
the traditional types of fiction. In fact, most of them didn't want to call it science fiction or

07:15.780 --> 07:16.980
speculative fiction or

07:19.140 --> 07:24.420
and they were interested in writing about interstates,

07:26.040 --> 07:28.420
rolling a lot of them, taking flight.

07:32.600 --> 07:38.080
But in the rather bitter internal school with one author,

07:38.320 --> 07:43.840
a lot of people take sides one way or the other. I think every one of them would have done it.

07:52.660 --> 07:57.160
But we need to remember here that the New Wave wasn't really a planned and deliberate movement

07:57.160 --> 08:01.380
by a unified group of writers. One of the principal proponents of the New Wave,

08:01.800 --> 08:06.300
author Norman Spenred, believes it was just a bunch of diverse writers doing their own thing.

08:07.220 --> 08:11.960
It was an old way, but there was never as a coherent philosophy in school of science fiction,

08:11.960 --> 08:16.460
but there was never a New Wave in the same sense. There were a lot of ways. There are a lot of

08:16.460 --> 08:20.840
different people doing a lot of different things. The people that were identified as the New Wave

08:20.840 --> 08:27.020
were very diverse. What I was actually writing is very different to what Tom Dish was writing,

08:27.260 --> 08:33.260
or Balaard, or Zalazny, or Delaney were also identified as New Wave writers. This stuff is

08:33.920 --> 08:39.060
much more than, you know, Zalazny and Delaney and myself and Balaard and Ardison and Mike,

08:39.060 --> 08:50.040
but there were more differences between our work and the old stuff. There was more difference

08:50.040 --> 08:53.380
within the so-called New Wave than there was within the so-called old Wave.

08:54.240 --> 08:58.420
But Spenred also thinks the New Wave was tightly connected to what was happening in society.

08:59.680 --> 09:04.180
Of course, this mirrored the cultural climate at the time. It mirrored what was happening politically,

09:04.180 --> 09:07.940
it mirrored what was happening in music, it mirrored what was happening in movies,

09:08.200 --> 09:12.440
it was a phenomenon that went through the western civilizations at home.

09:19.020 --> 09:24.080
There are those who say the New Wave is dead. Five-time Hugo winner Larry Nivens says so,

09:24.160 --> 09:30.140
for instance, and offers a reason for his passing. The New Wave is a very persuasive thing,

09:30.730 --> 09:39.800
and very easy to use to justify bad stories. I think that's what killed it. Not the

09:40.700 --> 09:49.740
increased characterization and experiments with typography and story format are a bad thing

09:49.740 --> 09:56.600
in themselves, but it's so easy to use New Wave to justify a bad story. It was bound to go out.

10:02.700 --> 10:07.040
The influence of the New Wave is still around, though. It's left its mark on the field.

10:07.520 --> 10:10.860
Science fiction has been broadened, maybe enhanced somehow because of it.

10:11.200 --> 10:12.580
Frederick Paul states it well.

10:13.640 --> 10:18.540
And the New Wave, if nothing else, taught a bunch of old dinosaurs like Asimov and

10:19.940 --> 10:25.180
Heinlein and me, that there were non-traditional ways of constructing a novel.

10:25.180 --> 10:29.460
See, most of us had grown up when science fiction was in the pulp magazine,

10:29.660 --> 10:33.340
and most of it was written according to some variant of a pulp formula.

10:34.460 --> 10:39.780
Well, it's necessary. I think the New Wave is responsible for teaching us that.

